 141 |     Treat this snapshot as context, not as a target to copy. Prefer the summary
 142 |     first; only read individual checkpoint programs when you need to understand
 143 |     a specific prior candidate. Use recent agentic traces only when you need to
 144 |     understand which tool calls, research paths, or reasoning steps led to the
 145 |     previous candidate.
 146 | 
 147 |     When reading iteration stats, distinguish the fields carefully:
 148 |     - `global.global_best_score` is the best score found up to and including
 149 |       that iteration.
 150 |     - `global.current_iteration_best_score` is the best score among programs
 151 |       produced in that specific iteration.
 152 |     - `iteration_result.child_program.metrics.combined_score` is the score of
 153 |       the newly generated child for that iteration.
 154 |     - A plateau means the child scores are failing to exceed the running best
 155 |       for several iterations, even if `global_best_score` remains high.
 156 | 
 157 |     ## Task
 158 |     Improve the `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` function in the EVOLVE-BLOCK.
 159 |     Build an explicit symbolic expression template using the `pysr_harness` API.
 160 | 
 161 |     Use `pysr_harness.equation_session` helpers:
 162 |     - `feature_symbols(n)` → PySR variables `x0`, `x1`, ...
 163 |     - `constant_symbols(n)` → tunable constants `c0`, `c1`, ...
 164 |     - `evaluate_expression(expr, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, constants=...)`
 165 |       fits constants via least-squares and returns scored metrics.
 166 | 
 167 |     ## Search Strategy
 168 |     Do not assume a particular equation family. Use the current candidate,
 169 |     prior scores, evaluator feedback, and any bounded diagnostics you choose
 170 |     to inspect to infer what structural change is justified.
 171 | 
 172 |     Understand exploration vs exploitation in this evolutionary search:
 173 |     - Exploration means deliberately moving to a different structural region
 174 |       when local mutations are not improving the running best. Use it to test
 175 |       a new principle, transformation, variable interaction, or stability idea.
 176 |       Exploration should still be disciplined: explain what failure mode or
 177 |       hypothesis the new structure targets.
 178 |     - Exploitation means refining a promising family after it shows improvement.
 179 |       Use it for small, controlled changes that preserve the useful behavior
 180 |       while addressing a clear limitation such as scaling, baseline behavior,
 181 |       numerical conditioning, or unnecessary complexity.
 182 |     - If recent child scores regress or duplicate the current best, switch from
 183 |       incremental tweaks to evidence gathering. Inspect run history, hard cases,
 184 |       and, when useful, external sources before proposing the next expression.
 185 |     - If a child improves substantially, exploit that direction with minimal
 186 |       changes rather than immediately replacing the whole structure.
 187 | 
 188 |     Before changing the expression, identify the most likely limitation:
 189 |     - poor fit quality on many datasets
 190 |     - non-finite predictions or invalid arithmetic on one or more datasets
 191 |     - excessive sensitivity to x0 or x1 scaling
 192 |     - over-parameterization that makes constant fitting unreliable
 193 |     - under-parameterization that cannot capture shared structure
 194 |     - a redundant term that adds complexity without improving robustness
 195 | 
 196 |     Prefer the smallest structural change that targets the limitation you
 197 |     identify. Do not add complexity merely because more constants are allowed.
 198 |     Because complexity has a small direct score penalty, every extra operation
 199 |     or fitted constant should have a clear expected payoff in validation fit or
 200 |     robustness.
 201 | 
 202 |     Good candidates are:
 203 |     - smooth and globally defined over the observed x0 and x1 ranges
 204 |     - numerically stable during least-squares fitting
 205 |     - compact enough for reliable optimization from one initial point
 206 |     - able to use x1 when it is informative without depending on it too strongly
 207 |     - robust on small, noisy, or unusually scaled datasets
 208 | 
 209 |     Be especially cautious with operations that can create singularities,
 210 |     non-real values, overflow, or invalid powers during fitting. If you use
 211 |     division, exponentials, logarithms, square roots, or variable exponents,
 212 |     explain why the resulting expression remains well behaved.
 213 | 
 214 |     Keep the number of fitted constants moderate. Too many constants risk
 215 |     unstable fits on small datasets; too few can underfit shared structure.
 216 | 
 217 |     ## Constraints
 218 |     - Exactly one call to `evaluate_expression(...)` per
 219 |       `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` invocation.
 220 |     - Directly `return evaluate_expression(...)`; do not assign the result to a
 221 |       variable, edit it, wrap it, or post-process it.
 222 |     - The `equation_template` returned by the scorer must be identical for every
 223 |       dataset; only fitted constant values may differ across datasets.
 224 |     - Keep `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` straight-line: no loops, conditionals,
 225 |       try/except blocks, nested functions/classes, comprehensions, helper
 226 |       function calls, or imports inside the function.
 227 |     - Do not use `Piecewise`, `Max`, `Min`, `sign`, `floor`, `ceiling`,
 228 |       `Heaviside`, relational/boolean expressions, or other gated/conditional
